  "prompt": "What Basel III means for banks?",
  "response": "Basel III is a global regulatory framework for banks, developed by the Basel Committee on Banking Supervision. Here are key implications for banks:\n\n1. Capital Requirements\n- Higher minimum capital ratios\n- Increased quality and quantity of capital reserves\n- Enhanced ability to absorb financial shocks\n- Improved bank stability and resilience\n\n2. Liquidity Standards\n- Introduction of Liquidity Coverage Ratio (LCR)\n- Requirement to maintain sufficient liquid assets\n- Ensures banks can survive short-term liquidity disruptions\n- Reduces risk of bank failures during financial stress\n\n3. Leverage Ratio\n- Limits excessive borrowing\n- Constrains bank's ability to take on high-risk investments\n- Provides additional buffer against potential losses\n\n4. Risk Management\n- More stringent risk assessment procedures\n- Enhanced monitoring of potential financial risks\n- Improved overall risk governance\n\n5. Compliance Costs\n- Significant investments in technology and infrastructure\n- Higher operational expenses\n- Potential reduction in profitability\n\n6. Balance Sheet Management\n- More conservative lending practices\n- Reduced risk-taking\n- Potentially lower returns on investment\n\n7. Global Banking Standardization\n- Uniform regulatory framework across countries\n- Promotes international banking stability\n- Reduces systemic financial risks\n\nThese changes aim to create a more stable and resilient global banking system.",
